posts.name: EricH
posts.cooked:
Can you point me to a place where they might be banned?

That said, I‚Äôm not quite sure what you mean by ‚Äúclear red‚Äù.

Longer answer: You‚Äôll need to pull up the 2021 Game Manual and turn to section 9.7: Power Distribution. Rule R40, paraphrased: From the battery to the PDP , including the Main Breaker, needs to be a minimum of 6AWG. ‚ÄìNOTE: 4 AWG is larger than 6 AWG, and is thus legal. Rule R53, paraphrased: Refer to table for MINIMUM wire sizes based on circuit breaker amperages. ‚ÄìNOTE: These are minimum sizes, and there‚Äôs no issue with using larger wires.

Here‚Äôs where you might run into trouble:

R56: All non-SIGNAL LEVEL wiring with a constant polarity (i.e., except for outputs of relay modules, motor controllers, or sensors) shall be color-coded along their entire length from the manufacturer as follows: A. Red, yellow, white, brown, or black-with-stripe on the positive (e.g. +24VDC, +12VDC, +5VDC, etc.) connections B. Black or blue for the common or negative side (-) of the connections. Exceptions to this rule include: C. Wires that are originally attached to legal devices and any extensions to these wires using the same color as the manufacturer. D. Ethernet cable used in POE cables.

You‚Äôre not going to run into either of the exceptions, I don‚Äôt think. So what you‚Äôre really asking is, is ‚Äúclear red‚Äù equivalent to ‚Äúred‚Äù?

If Amazon.com is anything to go by, the answer is ‚Äúprobably yes but it will depend on your inspector‚Äù.

EDIT: Given the above picture, and past experience as an inspector, 99% legal without any hassle, 1% chance that an inspector gives you a hard time but is overruled by a LRI . I‚Äôd call it legal, it‚Äôs clearly red and clearly marked as 4AWG.

Edit #2: Though I would be cautious of weight (4AWG wire being heavy), and proper fits into the PDP if you‚Äôre using it on anything other than the battery-to- PDP wire routing.

posts.name: Al Skierkiewicz  Learn Something New, Every Day!
posts.cooked: OK, to answer the first question, yes, the clear red insulation does meet the rule.  Tinned copper wire also meets the rule but may not be obvious to some inspectors who have no electrical background.  Ask to have your LRI rule on it if there is a question.  If the LRI does not have an answer, they will call me or Chuck for a ruling. Copper clad or copper plated aluminum is not legal under the rules listed above. As an additional note‚Ä¶ Clear insulation may not have the same temperature rating as other insulations.  If the insulation on your robot shows any deterioration, you may be asked to replace it.  Although it is not specified in the robot rules, insulation that deforms or becomes unstable under 100 degrees C is likely a poor choice for robot mains wiring.  I most often see clear insulation in speaker cables.

posts.name: Gus Michel II
posts.cooked: To determine whether your wire is copper or copper-clad, look at the cross section/cut face of the wire.  If you‚Äôre looking at copper, good to go. If you‚Äôre looking at something else (e.g. aluminum), don‚Äôt use it on an FRC robot unless you really like emergency re-wiring at competition.

posts.name: Tristan Lall
posts.cooked:
Copper-clad aluminum is great in applications that don‚Äôt see temperature extremes and are sensitive to weight. Its conductivity-to-weight ratio is better than pure copper. The copper cladding makes it (mostly; not strictly in critical applications) crimpable using ordinary lugs designed for copper, and it isn‚Äôt completely unsolderable with ordinary tools and materials (but crimps are usually better). In many ways it is actually perfect for FRC, except for the fact that it is not permitted. Its reputation probably comes from being corruptly substituted for copper at a given gauge, because its conductivity per cross-sectional area is lower than copper.

However, it is hard to find copper-clad aluminum wire with the same array of insulation options and certifications as copper wire, as these applications are esoteric.
